   As owners of 2/3 of the land base, the Nations farmers and ranchers are
   the primary stewards of our soil and water. They have sustained our
   private land for generations. The value of their careful land
   stewardship extends beyond the fences of farms and ranches. It brings
   the benefits of healthy soil and clean water to people and communities
   throughout the Nation and the world. The U.S. Department of Agriculture
   (USDA) and its partners support them in their stewardship through
   conservation technical assistance, the basic conservation
   infrastructure. All farmers and ranchers can seek technical assistance
   from USDAs Natural Resources Conservation Service (NRCS) through local
   conservation districts. Together, they work to create and put into
   action conservation plans that are designed to improve the quality and
   productivity of their land. [shim.gif]
   Sec. Dan Glickman
   To build upon and strengthen this important relationship that USDA has
       with those who make their living from the land, Secretary Glickman
       has proposed this Conservation Initiative as a key part of the
       overall safety net package. The initiative is based on the
       following four principles:

"Principles I believe in . . .

   [shim.gif]
   [shim.gif]
   Broadening farm policy 1. Broadening farm policy to include more
   farmers and ranchers [shim.gif]
   Non-traditional comodities 2. Farm policy must be national in scope,
   not just geared towards traditional farm commodities [shim.gif]
   valuable land 3. We must treat land and water, not just crops, as
   valuable commodities. [shim.gif]
   Maine Potatoes 4. We need to provide more assistance to those who need
   it most.

   In short, were talking about more producers, more crops, more areas."
   [shim.gif]
